<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: DELUCA FAILS TO REGAIN FLYWEIGHT TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE MCKIBBEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Diego's Tony "Bazooka" DeLuca failed in his attempt to regain the North 
American Boxing Federation flyweight championship Wednesday night at the Sports 
Arena by losing a unanimous 12-round decision to Blythe's Ysaias Zamudio. 
</P>
<P>
The defeat is DeLuca's third in a row and lowers his professional record to 
17-5-3. 
</P>
<P>
Zamudio (21-3), ranked No. 1 by the World Boxing Assn., dominated the fight 
throughout and never gave DeLuca an opportunity to land any effective blows. 
</P>
<P>
Zamudio was the much quicker fighter and he cut DeLuca's right eye in the 11th 
round. 
</P>
<P>
"He was a little fast," DeLuca said. "I think he was quicker than (Michael) 
Carbajal and he was a little more unorthodox than Carbajal." 
</P>
<P>
Asked if he will continue fighting, DeLuca said: "I've got boxing in my blood. 
I'd have to be talked into giving it up by my trainers." DAVE MCKIBBEN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120690-0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 318192 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 6, 1990, Thursday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
