<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ MAKES A SPELLBINDING ENTRANCE; 
</P>
<P>
TRIAL: PROSPECTIVE JURORS ARE QUESTIONED AS THE ACTRESS AND A FORMER BOYFRIEND 
PREPARE TO DO LEGAL BATTLE OVER 'PASSION' PERFUME. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CAROL McGRAW, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was a grand entrance. 
</P>
<P>
Oscar-winning actress Elizabeth Taylor -- looking thin and rich -- walked 
regally across the width of the Los Angeles Superior Court hearing room to her 
seat at the counsel table as spellbound prospective jurors looked on. 
</P>
<P>
Her brilliant purple suede suit with matching purple handbag and purple 
reptilian high-heel shoes contrasted sharply with the subdued business suits 
worn by two legal teams gathered to do battle in a multimillion-dollar lawsuit 
involving rights to her perfume Passion. She wore four tiers of chunky pearls 
around a neckline that plunged. 
</P>
<P>
At the opposite end of the counsel table sat her adversary, former used-car 
salesman Henry Wynberg, a former jet-set boyfriend who was photographered with 
Taylor in many exotic locations during their two-year relationship in the 
mid-1970s. 
</P>
<P>
The former lovers did not look at one another. 
</P>
<P>
But the 50 potential jurors did a lot of looking. Some ventured only polite 
sideways glances at the woman they had seen in movie theaters and on 
television. Others stared boldly. Taylor, in turn, turned around in her seat 
and looked directly at the jury pool with her violet eyes. 
</P>
<P>
At stake in the trial is more than $70 million a year in profits from the 
highly popular line of Passion fragrances and cosmetics that Taylor launched 
with Chesbrough-Ponds in 1987, and which has been a spectacular seller. 
</P>
<P>
Taylor sued Wynberg in 1986, just as she was ready to launch a $30-million 
advertising campaign for Passion. She had signed a cosmetics contract with him 
in 1975 and wanted out of the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement gave Wynberg perpetual rights to 30% of the net profits to any 
cosmetics marketed under her name. She also alleged that Wynberg did not live 
up to his end of the contract. 
</P>
<P>
Wynberg, in turn, sued Taylor for breach of contract, fraud and 
misappropriation, contending that Passion was a copycat of a fragrance that he 
had developed years earlier. The potential jurors were questioned in detail as 
to whether they "had any experience with Passion perfume, whether they approved 
of Taylor's fund-raising efforts for AIDS-related causes, and whether they had 
known anyone who had alcohol abuse problems. Taylor's attorney, Neil Papiano, 
told the jurors that Taylor had had alcohol problems and had been rehabilitated 
at the Betty Ford Clinic in Rancho Mirage. 
</P>
<P>
Only two women said they regularly splashed on Passion. 
</P>
<P>
The question about AIDS was asked by Papiano because Taylor donates a portion 
of her profits from Passion perfume to the AIDS charities. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Judge Coleman Swart refused to bar Wynberg's past criminal 
record from being introduced at the trial. 
</P>
<P>
Wynberg's attorney, state Sen. Quentin Kopp (I-San Francisco), sought to 
prevent jurors from hearing about Wynberg's 1977 misdemeanor conviction and 
90-day jail sentence for contributing to the delinquency of a minor. Wynberg 
had been arrested on suspicion of fondling a 16-year-old girl during a 
photography session with another man and four Beverly Hills High School girls 
at his home. 
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for Taylor argued that those issues were crucial to proving that she 
was justified in breaking off her business relationship with Wynberg "because 
any reputable cosmetics company would refuse to deal with Wynberg." 
</P>
<P>
Both Wynberg and Taylor are expected to testify at the three-week trial, as 
will a host of chemical and perfume experts who will provide a glimpse of the 
$4 billion-a-year cosmetics industry. 
</P>
<P>
As Taylor left the courtroom through a side door, Irwin Meyer, a Los Angeles 
attorney who was in court on another matter, asked one of Taylor's lawyers to 
get him an autograph. Papiano returned with the postcard signed by the star. 
</P>
<P>
"Not everyone can carry out an outfit like that," said an enthused Meyer. "It 
brings out the star in her. The shoes were just perfect." 
</P>
</TEXT>
