<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
GERMANY TO FIGHT SPORTS DOPING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BERLIN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Top German sports officials said today that drug testing will be radically 
stepped up in all sports, following allegations of massive doping by German 
athletes. 
</P>
<P>
Hans Hansen, president of the German Sports Federation, outlined a 12-point 
program to combat drug use following a more than three-hour meeting of sports 
officials in the German capital. 
</P>
<P>
Hansen told a news conference that the federation would not wait for 
international recommendations to fight the use of drugs, but would seek to play 
an active role in cleaning up German sports. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a prominent judge was appointed to head an independent commission 
that will investigate published allegations that many top stars in former East 
Germany, as well as some track and field athletes from former West Germany, 
regularly took performance-enhancing drugs. Heinrich Reiter, the 60-year-old 
president of the federal social court, will head the commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
